  String get diabetes => '1. Diabetes\n\nğŸ©º What is Diabetes?\n\nâ€¢ Diabetes is a long-term condition where your body has trouble using sugar (called glucose) from your food.\nâ€¢ Normally, a hormone called insulin helps carry sugar from your blood into your bodyâ€™s cells for energy.\nâ€¢ In diabetes, your body either doesn\'t make enough insulin or doesnâ€™t use it well, causing sugar to stay in your blood.\nâ€¢ Too much sugar in the blood for a long time can harm your heart, kidneys, eyes, and nerves.\nâš ï¸ Common Symptoms (What People May Feel)\nâ€¢ ğŸ¥µ Feeling very thirsty often: You may drink more water than usual and still feel dry.\nâ€¢ ğŸš½ Frequent urination: You may go to the toilet more, especially at night.\nâ€¢ ğŸ˜´ Feeling tired all the time: You might feel sleepy or weak, even after resting.\nâ€¢ ğŸ‘€ Blurry vision: Your eyesight might suddenly seem less clear.\nâ€¢ âš–ï¸ Losing weight without trying: This can happen even when you are eating well.\nâ€¢ ğŸ©¹ Cuts that heal slowly: Small wounds or infections might take longer to get better.\nâ€¢ ğŸ¦¶ Numbness or tingling: You may feel pins and needles in your hands or feet.\nğŸ§  Why It Matters\nâ€¢ Diabetes doesn\'t always show symptoms early, but over time it can cause serious health issues.\nâ€¢ It increases your risk for heart problems, kidney failure, eye damage, and nerve pain.\nâ€¢ If not treated, it may even lead to stroke or limb damage (requiring amputation in extreme cases).\nâ€¢ The good news: with lifestyle changes and care, it can be managed well.\nâœ… What You Can Do (Precautions and Home Care)\nğŸ½ï¸ Eat Smarter\nâ€¢ Avoid sugary snacks and soft drinks: These quickly raise your blood sugar.\nâ€¢ Eat more vegetables, whole grains (like brown rice), and fresh fruits: They help control sugar levels.\nâ€¢ Reduce oily and fried food: These can lead to weight gain and worsen blood sugar.\nâ€¢ Donâ€™t skip meals: Eating at regular times helps maintain balanced sugar levels.\nğŸƒ Stay Physically Active\nâ€¢ Aim for at least 30 minutes of walking or light activity every day.\nâ€¢ Simple activities like cleaning, playing with kids, or doing housework also help.\nâ€¢ Physical movement helps your body use insulin better.\nğŸ“‰ Manage Your Weight\nâ€¢ Even small weight loss (like 5â€“10% of your body weight) can make a big difference in sugar control.\nâ€¢ Obesity is a strong risk factor for type 2 diabetes.\nğŸ§ª Monitor & Get Checked\nâ€¢ Check your blood sugar if you are over 35, overweight, or if someone in your family has diabetes.\nâ€¢ Early testing helps you take action before it becomes serious.\nğŸš­ Say No To...\nâ€¢ Smoking: It worsens blood flow and can damage your organs faster.\nâ€¢ Alcohol: It can increase or suddenly drop blood sugar, both of which are dangerous.\nâ€¢ Sugary drinks: Switch to water, buttermilk, or unsweetened tea.\nğŸ§˜â€â™€ï¸ Mental and Emotional Care\nâ€¢ Diabetes can be stressful. You might feel anxious or frustrated about lifestyle changes.\nâ€¢ Talk to someoneâ€”friends, family, or a counselor. You\'re not alone.\nâ€¢ Stress itself can raise blood sugar, so keeping calm really helps.\nğŸ“Œ When to See a Doctor\nâ€¢ If you notice symptoms mentioned above, especially blurred vision, tiredness, or frequent urination.\nâ€¢ If you have wounds that donâ€™t heal or numbness in hands/feet.\nâ€¢ For regular sugar testingâ€”even if you feel okay.\n';
